{"title_page": "Just a Little Lovin' (Carmen McRae album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Just a Little Lovin'\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Carmen McRae]]\n| cover      = Carmen McRae - Just a Little Lovin'.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1970\n| recorded   = February 16, 1970 <small>& May 18, 1970</small>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Atlantic South-Criteria Studio, [[Miami, FL]] <small>& [[Atlantic Studios]], [[New York City|New York]]</small>\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 35:26\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] <small>SD 1568</small>\n| producer   = [[Arif Mardin]]\n| chronology = [[Carmen McRae]]\n| prev_title = [[Portrait of Carmen]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[November Girl]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\n'''''Just a Little Lovin'''''' is a 1970 [[studio album]] by [[Carmen McRae]] directed and produced by [[Arif Mardin]].<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|last=|first=|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=just-a-little-lovin-mw0000263763|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|title=Just a Little Lovin'|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> The recording in a studio of Atlantic Records in Miami was set up with a horn section, an occasional string section and [[The Sweet Inspirations]] as backing vocals on some tracks. The studio's own Dixie Flyers, a rhythm section founded by [[Sammy Creason]], provided the contemporary electrified sound for a repertoire that derived mainly from only recently written [[pop song|pop songs]], three alone by [[the Beatles]], two by the [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio|Muscle Shoal crew]] like \"[[Breakfast in Bed]]\", written in 1968 for [[Dusty Springfield]], and a [[Laura Nyro]] original. The electrified orchestral sound is advanced twice, on \"[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]\" with the use of a [[cimbalom]] (remotely similar sounding like a [[sitar]]), and with a [[Mellotron]] on \"[[What'cha Gonna Do]]\" that harmonizes with the strings. Slightly out of the pop vein are a straightforwardly played [[blues shuffle]], \"[[I Love the Life I Live]]\" by [[Willie Dixon]], and \"Didn't We\", an intimate duet with guitarist [[Al Gafa]]. \nThere were several singles issued before and alongside the album's release, although the songs chosen for the most part didn't make it on the final album.<ref>Atlantic 45-2691, 1969 \n{{Discogs master|master=1505782|name=I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\u2013Just a Dream Ago|type=single}}</ref><ref>Atlantic 45-2736, 1970 \n{{Discogs master|master=1347039|name=Just a Little Lovin'\u2013I Want You|type=single}}</ref><ref>Atlantic 45-2776, 1971 \n{{Discogs master|master=1303093|name=Carry That Weight\u2013Goodbye Joe|type=single}}</ref> They were reissued in 1991 as additional tracks on a Japanese digital re-release.<ref>Atlantic Japan AMCY-1079, \nLadies Sing Jazz Series, 1991 {{Discogs release|9075328|Just a Little Lovin'|type=album}}</ref> \"I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\" and \"Just a Dream\" were recorded already in September of 1969 and Mardin had not thought of a horn section yet, instead the strings are emphasized.<ref>[https://jazzdiscography.com/Artists/carmen-mcrae/carmen-mcrae-70s-discography.php Cf. personnel on Carmen McRae's sessionography for the 1970s on Jazzdiscography.com]</ref> \n\n==Track listing==\n# \"Just a Little Lovin'\" ([[Barry Mann]], [[Cynthia Weil]]) - 2:15\n# \"[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]\" ([[George Harrison]]) - 3:07\n# \"I Thought I Knew You Well\" ([[Tony Joe White]]) - 3:42\n# \"[[The Early Years (album series)|I Want You]]\" ([[Tom Waits]]) - 2:10\n# \"[[More Today Than Yesterday]]\" ([[Pat Upton (singer)|Patrick Upton]]) - 2:59\n# \"[[Here, There and Everywhere]]\" ([[John Lennon and Paul McCartney|John Lennon, Paul McCartney]]) - 2:32\n# \"[[Carry That Weight]]\" (Lennon, McCartney) - 2:45\n# \"[[Breakfast in Bed]]\" ([[Donnie Fritts]], [[Eddie Hinton]]) - 3:12\n# \"[[I Love the Life I Live]]\" ([[Willie Dixon]]) - 2:25\n# \"[[What'cha Gonna Do]]\" (Donnie Fritts, John Reid) - 3:35\n# \"Didn't We\" ([[Jim Webb]]) - 3:22\n# \"Goodbye Joe\" ([[Laura Nyro]]) - 2:30\n;Bonus tracks on 1991 Japanese Atlantic release (AMCY-1079)\n#<li value=\"13\"> \"I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\" ([[Al Kooper]]) - 3:37\n# \"Just a Dream\" ([[Bobby Worth]]) - 3:16 \t\n# \"Silent Spring\" (Allan Paul Shatkin) - 3:05\n\n''All tracks were recorded February 2, 1970, at Atlantic South-Criteria Studio in Miami, Florida, except \"Didn't We\" recorded May 18, 1970, at [[Atlantic Studios|Atlantic Studios in New York]]. The single tracks \"I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\" and \"Just a Dream\" were recorded September 15, 1969, at Regent Sound Studio, NY,<ref>[https://jazzdiscography.com/Artists/carmen-mcrae/carmen-mcrae-60s-discography.php Cf. Carmen McRae's sessionography for the 1960s on Jazzdiscography.com]</ref> and \"Silent Spring\" in March 1970 at Atlantic Studios in New York.<ref>[https://jazzdiscography.com/Artists/carmen-mcrae/carmen-mcrae-70s-discography.php Cf. Carmen McRae's sessionography for the 1970s on Jazzdiscography.com]</ref>''\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Carmen McRae]] - [[singing|vocals]]\n*[[Arif Mardin]] - arranger, musical direction\n*Horn section <small>(on all tracks except 11, 13-15)</small>\n**[[King Curtis]] - alto saxophone, tenor saxophone (soloist)\n**George Dorsey - alto saxophone\n**[[Pepper Adams]] - baritone saxophone\n**[[Joe Newman (trumpeter)|Joe Newman]] - trumpet (soloist)\n**[[Garnett Brown]] - trombone\n**Wally Kane, George Marge, Romeo Penque - woodwind\n**Joseph DeAngelis, Anthony Miranda, Brooks Tillotson - french horn\n*The Dixie Flyers: \n**[[Mike Utley]] - electric piano, organ\n**[[Jim Dickinson]] - guitar, keyboards\n**Charlie Freeman - lead guitar\n**Tommy McClure - bass\n**[[Sammy Creason]] - drums, percussion\n*[[The Sweet Inspirations]] - backing vocals <small>(2, 3, 7, 12, 13)</small>\n*Unknown string section conducted by [[Gene Orloff]] <small>(1, 2, 7, 10, 13-15)</small>\n;\"Didn't We\" is a duo with\n*[[Al Gafa]] - guitar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Carmen McRae}}\n\n[[Category:1970 albums]]\n[[Category:Carmen McRae albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Arif Mardin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Just a Little Lovin'\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Carmen McRae]]\n| cover      = Carmen McRae - Just a Little Lovin'.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1970\n| recorded   = February 16, 1970 <small>& May 18, 1970</small>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Atlantic South-Criteria Studio, [[Miami, FL]] <small>& [[Atlantic Studios]], [[New York City|New York]]</small>\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[Pop]]\n| length     = 35:26\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] <small>SD 1568</small>\n| producer   = [[Arif Mardin]]\n| chronology = [[Carmen McRae]]\n| prev_title = [[Portrait of Carmen]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[November Girl]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\n'''''Just a Little Lovin'''''' is a 1970 [[studio album]] by [[Carmen McRae]] directed and produced by [[Arif Mardin]].<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|last=|first=|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=just-a-little-lovin-mw0000263763|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|title=Just a Little Lovin'|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> The recording in a studio of Atlantic Records in Miami was set up with a horn section, an occasional string section and [[The Sweet Inspirations]] as backing vocals on some tracks. The studio's own Dixie Flyers, a rhythm section founded by [[Sammy Creason]], provided the contemporary electrified sound for a repertoire that derived mainly from only recently written [[pop song|pop songs]], three alone by [[the Beatles]], two by the [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio|Muscle Shoal crew]] like \"[[Breakfast in Bed]]\", written in 1968 for [[Dusty Springfield]], and a [[Laura Nyro]] original. The electrified orchestral sound is advanced twice, on \"[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]\" with the use of a [[cimbalom]] (remotely similar sounding like a [[sitar]]), and with a [[Mellotron]] on \"[[What'cha Gonna Do]]\" that harmonizes with the strings. Slightly out of the pop vein are a straightforwardly played [[blues shuffle]], \"[[I Love the Life I Live]]\" by [[Willie Dixon]], and \"Didn't We\", an intimate duet with guitarist [[Al Gafa]]. \nThere were several singles issued before and alongside the album's release, although the songs chosen for the most part didn't make it on the final album.<ref>Atlantic 45-2691, 1969 \n{{Discogs master|master=1505782|name=I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\u2013Just a Dream Ago|type=single}}</ref><ref>Atlantic 45-2736, 1970 \n{{Discogs master|master=1347039|name=Just a Little Lovin'\u2013I Want You|type=single}}</ref><ref>Atlantic 45-2776, 1971 \n{{Discogs master|master=1303093|name=Carry That Weight\u2013Goodbye Joe|type=single}}</ref> They were reissued in 1991 as additional tracks on a Japanese digital re-release.<ref>Atlantic Japan AMCY-1079, \nLadies Sing Jazz Series, 1991 {{Discogs release|9075328|Just a Little Lovin'|type=album}}</ref> \"I Love You More Than You'll Ever Know\" and \"Just a Dream\" were recorded already in September of 1969 and Mardin had not thought of a horn section yet, instead the strings are emphasized.<ref>[https://jazzdiscography.com/Artists/carmen-mcrae/carmen-mcrae-70s-discography.php Cf. personnel on Carmen McRae's sessionography for the 1970s on Jazzdiscography.com]</ref> \n\n==Track listing==\n# \"Just a Little Lovin'\" ([[Barry Mann]], [[Cynthia Weil]]) - 2:15\n# \"[[Something (Beatles song)|Something]]\" ([[George Harrison]]) - 3:07\n# \"I Thought I Knew You Well\" ([[Tony Joe White]]) - 3:42\n# \"[[The Early Years (album series)|I Want You]]\" (